    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>pre-roll ad</strong> is a video advertisement that plays automatically before the main video content a user chose to watch. On YouTube, skippable pre-roll ads can be skipped after 5 seconds; non-skippable formats run 15-20 seconds with no opt-out. Advertisers pay per view (CPV) or per thousand impressions (CPM), making pre-roll one of the <strong>most targeted and measurable video ad formats</strong> in digital marketing.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Standard lengths</div>
            <div class="tms-value">6s / 15s / 30s</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg. CPV (YouTube)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$0.01 - $0.30</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Pre-roll ads have a 5-second window to earn a viewer's attention or lose them to the skip button. That constraint forces creative discipline that most other ad formats don't demand. Done right, pre-roll delivers brand awareness at scale and direct-response results for audiences already consuming video in your category.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a pre-roll ad?</h2>
        <p>A pre-roll ad is a video ad format that appears before (pre), during (mid-roll), or after (post-roll) video content on platforms including YouTube, Facebook, Instagram, and programmatic video networks. "Pre-roll" specifically refers to the before-video placement — the most common and highest-impact position.</p>
        <p>Pre-roll ads fall into two broad categories:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skippable pre-roll (TrueView)</strong> — YouTube's standard format. Users can skip after 5 seconds. Advertisers pay when users watch 30 seconds or the entire ad (whichever comes first). Average skip rate: 65-75%.</li>
          <li><strong>Non-skippable pre-roll</strong> — 15-20 second ads with no skip option. Users must watch the entire ad. Charged on CPM. Higher tolerance for brand messages; lower tolerance for direct response.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>A third format — the <strong>bumper ad</strong> — is a 6-second non-skippable pre-roll used for brand reinforcement, typically as part of a sequential campaign.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">YouTube's TrueView model</div>
          <p>Google's TrueView skippable pre-roll is unique because <strong>advertisers only pay for engaged views</strong>. If a user skips at second 4, you owe nothing. This makes TrueView one of the most cost-efficient top-of-funnel formats when creative is strong enough to retain viewers past the 5-second mark.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why pre-roll ads matter for digital advertisers</h2>
        <p>Pre-roll's position — before the content a user specifically chose to watch — gives it contextual relevance that display and social feed ads lack. Here's why it matters:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>High-intent context.</strong> A user watching a video about project management software is in a relevant mindset when your PM tool ad plays. Contextual targeting amplifies this further.</li>
          <li><strong>Forced attention window.</strong> Even skippable ads have 5 guaranteed seconds. Compared to display ads that can be ignored entirely, pre-roll commands attention before viewers have the option to opt out.</li>
          <li><strong>DTC performance at scale.</strong> One DTC skincare brand found a single pre-roll format drove 3x more engagement than their static display equivalents targeting the same audience — the same creative investment, radically different results.</li>
          <li><strong>Sequential storytelling.</strong> Bumper ads, skippable ads, and retargeting ads can be sequenced. Show the problem (bumper), explain the solution (30-second skippable), close the deal (retargeted mid-roll). No other format enables this narrative arc at video scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Measurable beyond impressions.</strong> View-through rate, earned actions (channel subscribes, site visits after viewing), and brand lift studies give pre-roll measurability that outdoor or TV advertising can't match.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How pre-roll ads work technically</h2>
        <p>Pre-roll delivery runs through an ad server that inserts video ads into the content stream before playback begins. On YouTube, this operates through Google Ads' Video campaigns. On third-party sites, it typically runs through programmatic buyers using VAST (Video Ad Serving Template) tags.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Pre-roll delivery sequence</span><br>
          1. User clicks video on YouTube / publisher site<br>
          2. Player requests video from content CDN<br>
          3. <span class="uf-label">Simultaneously:</span> Ad server receives auction request<br>
          4. <span class="uf-status">Auction completes in ~100ms</span> — winning ad VAST tag returned<br>
          5. Pre-roll ad loads from advertiser's CDN<br>
          6. Ad plays before content<br>
          7. <span class="uf-new">Skip button appears at 5 seconds (skippable format)</span><br>
          8. <span class="uf-comment"># If user watches 30s or full ad: impression charged</span><br>
          9. Main video content begins
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of pre-roll ads — formats compared</h2>

