              <tr><td><strong>Masthead</strong></td><td>30s</td><td>Yes</td><td>CPD (reserved)</td><td>Product launches, mass reach</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real pre-roll ad examples that worked</h2>

        <h3>1. DTC skincare brand — format test drives 3x engagement</h3>
        <p>A direct-to-consumer skincare brand tested two creative approaches: a polished 30-second lifestyle ad and a raw 15-second "before/after" format with direct narration. The before/after format drove 3x more engagement (site visits, product page views) at the same budget. The lesson: authenticity and speed beat production value in pre-roll.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B consultant — LinkedIn reach surge</h3>
        <p>A B2B consultant ran pre-roll ads on LinkedIn Video targeting senior marketers at companies with 100-500 employees. Post reach went from 200 to 2,000+ views per video when paired with pre-roll exposure in the same week — halo effect from repeated exposure across video and feed formats.</p>

        <h3>3. Local restaurant — building community reach</h3>
        <p>A restaurant running Facebook pre-roll ads targeting local food interest audiences built a 15,000-person following in 8 months. The key was pairing pre-roll with a consistent organic posting schedule — the ads created reach, the organic content created retention.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Pre-roll ads vs display ads — which to use</h2>
        <p>Both run programmatically, but they produce different outcomes for different funnel stages.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Pre-roll advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>5+ guaranteed seconds of attention</li>
              <li>Contextual relevance via content adjacency</li>
              <li>Sequential storytelling across formats</li>
              <li>Pay-per-engaged-view (TrueView)</li>
              <li>Brand lift measurable via lift studies</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Display ad advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Lower production cost (static image vs video)</li>
              <li>Easier to A/B test rapidly</li>
              <li>Works for bottom-funnel retargeting</li>
              <li>Broader inventory reach</li>
              <li>No creative length constraints</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for pre-roll ads that don't get skipped</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Win in the first 5 seconds.</strong> Hook, problem, or disruption must land before the skip button appears. The viewer decides in 3-5 seconds whether to watch. Don't waste that window on a logo animation.</li>
          <li><strong>Show the brand in the first 3 seconds.</strong> Most users who skip will at least see 5 seconds. If you're building brand awareness, your brand identity needs to appear before the skip button does.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the ad length to the objective.</strong> Brand awareness: 15-30 seconds. Brand reinforcement and retargeting: 6-second bumpers. Direct response with product complexity: 30-60 seconds with strong CTA at second 20.</li>
          <li><strong>Use contextual targeting, not just demographic.</strong> An ad for productivity software placed before "how to manage a remote team" videos outperforms the same ad placed broadly by 3-5x. Contextual signals are your strongest pre-roll lever.</li>
          <li><strong>Design for muted playback.</strong> Facebook and Instagram auto-play video without sound. Include captions from the first frame so your message lands even in silent mode.</li>
          <li><strong>Test short vs long creative at the same budget.</strong> A 6-second bumper and a 30-second skippable ad often perform comparably in brand recall studies. Test before assuming longer is better.</li>
          <li><strong>Sequence your ads across the funnel.</strong> Use bumper ads for initial reach, skippable ads for consideration, and retargeted mid-roll for conversion. Sequential campaigns produce 70% higher purchase intent than single-format campaigns (Google internal data).</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating pre-roll as a TV spot</div>
          <p>TV ads are designed for captive audiences who cannot skip. Pre-roll ads play to audiences who have an escape hatch at 5 seconds. A 30-second brand story that builds slowly to a reveal works on TV; it fails on pre-roll. Recut your TV spots for online placement — lead with the payoff, not the setup.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common pre-roll ad mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Slow start</strong> — opening with logo animations, music build-ups, or slow reveals. Users skip at second 5; your hook must land at second 2-3.</li>
          <li><strong>No caption</strong> — 60-80% of social video plays without sound. A pre-roll with no text overlay loses its message for most mobile viewers.</li>
          <li><strong>Wrong format for the goal</strong> — using non-skippable ads for direct response (higher cost, higher friction) when TrueView would deliver the same click at half the cost.</li>
          <li><strong>No frequency cap</strong> — showing the same pre-roll to the same person 20+ times creates ad fatigue and brand aversion. Cap frequency at 3-5 impressions per week per user.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring view-through conversions</strong> — users who see your pre-roll but don't click often convert via organic search later. Track view-through attribution with a 7-day or 30-day window to see true campaign impact.</li>
        </ul>

